= Chapter 9: The Fate of Luminos-Vara
\ 
The giant Warden stood directly over Valen, a towering mountain of corrupted deepslate and pulsing midnight-blue veins. The darkness effect was slowly fading from Valen's eyes, revealing the terrifying reality: the monster's heavy stone fists were raised high, cast in the eerie, cold glow of its own corrupted heart.

Thum-thum. Thum-thum.

The heartbeat of the skulk vibrated through the floorboards, straight into Valen’s injured ankle. He couldn't run. He couldn't even stand.

The Warden tilted its faceless head down. Its long, bone-white antenna twitched, locking onto the sound of Valen’s ragged, terrified breathing. It let out a low, warning rumble that rattled the loose teeth in Valen's mouth.

"Please," Valen whispered, his voice cracking with heartbreak. He looked up into the chest of the machine—at the beautiful Echo Crystal he had placed there with his own hands, now stained an oily, dark blue. "I know you're in there. You're our protector."

For a single, fleeting second, the Warden paused. The angry midnight-blue light in its chest flickered, and a faint, familiar teal spark from Valen’s original design tried to push through the darkness. The machine hummed a tiny, broken note of its old, peaceful melody.

But the skulk was too strong.

Deep from the dark alleys, a nearby Skulk Sensor clicked. The vibration surged through the carpet of moss, straight into the Warden's feet. The peaceful spark was instantly choked out. The Warden’s antenna snapped wide open, and it let out a roar so loud it shattered the remaining glass windows across the plaza. It raised its massive arms to crush its creator.

Valen didn't think. He acted on pure instinct.

His hand darted out and scooped up his fallen golden tuning fork. With his remaining strength, he struck it hard against his iron apprentice knife.

PINGGGGG!

The fork vibrated with a brilliant, high-pitched ring. The Warden’s head snapped toward the sound in its immediate radius. Before the giant fists could slam down, Valen hurls the ringing tuning fork with all his might across the plaza, aiming straight into the deep, dark chasm of the lower mining tunnels.

The Warden didn't hesitate. Driven by its corrupted programming to destroy the source of any vibration, the giant beast spun around and lunged after the flying metal. It sprinted away from Valen, its heavy stone feet tearing up the cobblestone as it dove headfirst into the dark tunnel, disappearing into the depths after the fading ring of the fork.

Before Valen could even exhale, a pair of strong hands grabbed him under his arms and dragged him backward onto the safe, quiet wool path.

"I've got you, my boy! I've got you!" Master Elian hissed, his face streaked with sweat and soot.

"Master Elian! You're alive!" Valen gasped as the old engineer pulled him into the shadows of a deepslate archway.

"No time to celebrate," Elian whispered urgently, pointing toward the main avenues of the city.

The Grand Gateway was closed, but the infection had already won. The midnight-blue skulk was growing at a terrifying, unnatural speed, feeding on the echoes of the battle. It was swallowing the houses, climbing the towers, and carpeting the grand walkways. Dozens of other corrupted Wardens were wandering through the streets, their sonic booms echoing in the distance as they hunted down the last remaining sounds of the metropolis.

"The city is lost," Elian said, his eyes filled with tears as he looked at the darkening streets of Luminos-Vara. "The skulk is everywhere. We have to leave. Now."

Supported by Elian, Valen hobbled along the wool paths, joining a quiet, ghostly line of surviving citizens. They weren't inventors or guards anymore; they were refugees. They sneaked through the secret, winding escape tunnels that led up, up, and up toward the surface world.

At the entrance of the final tunnel, Valen stopped and looked back one last time.

The beautiful city of lights was gone. The bright blue soul lanterns were completely choked out. Down below, in the deep dark, lay a silent, ruined maze of deepslate structures, completely buried under a thick, pulsing blanket of star-speckled moss. The proud citizens who had built it would scatter to the surface, eventually splitting into different factions—some becoming peaceful villagers, others becoming hardened illagers—forgetting that they were once one people.

Luminos-Vara was dead. In its place, the dark, echoing tomb of the Ancient City was born.

From the shadows of the ruins below, a distant, ghostly thum-thum echoed up the shaft, a warning to anyone who would ever dare to come back down and disturb the silence.

The Legend of the Deep Dark
Centuries later, adventurers from the surface world would find these ruined cities. They would see the giant, empty deepslate frames in the center, the broken redstone lines, and the mysterious wool carpets lining the corridors—never knowing that a brave young apprentice named Valen once walked those very paths to save his people from the silence.